{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01WUEtX4BCeKq9HurPzdyngx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so the existing page uses `useParams` which is the client-side approach. I need to convert this to a Server Component that uses `params` as a Promise. The API route uses:\n\n```typescript\nconst { id } = await ctx.params;\n```\n\nSo in the page component, it should be:\n\n```typescript\nexport default async function UserProfilePage({ params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }) {\n  const { id } = await params;\n  const resolved_id = decodeURIComponent(id);\n\n\n```\n\nNow I'm fetching the user profile data, but here's the problem: even when the user doesn't exist (like \"test\" in the seed data), the testid attributes need to be present in the initial HTML for the HTTP checks to pass. This means I should render the component structure regardless of whether the profile fetch succeeds or fails.\n\nThe safest approach is wrapping the getUserProfile call in error handling so the page still renders the required testid containers even if ClickHouse isn't available or the user doesn't exist.\n\nNow I'm structuring the JSX to ensure both `identity-cluster` and `user-timeline` containers are always present in the DOM, with conditional content inside them based on whether the profile loaded successfully. But I'm realizing UserTimeline is already a client component, so I need to think through how that affects server-side rendering.\n\nClient components still get SSR'd for the initial HTML in Next.js App Router—the `\"use client\"` directive just marks where hydration happens. So the test IDs will definitely be in the rendered HTML regardless of the profile state. This approach works: keep the page as a server component, fetch the profile server-side with proper error handling, and always render the test containers so they're available for testing even if data fails to load.\n\nNow I'm realizing there's a tension between the sprint contract (which expects `\"use client\"` in the page file) and the eval feedback (which says to remove it). But the eval feedback is explicit about what needs fixing—the HTTP checks are failing because those test IDs aren't in the SSR HTML, and removing `\"use client\"` is the only way to get them there. The sprint 2 goal is to fix those failing checks, so I need to follow the eval guidance and remove the directive.\n\nAs for the `useUserProfile` hook, it can stay as-is since its tests already pass. The hook won't be used in the page anymore once it becomes a Server Component, but that's fine—it's there if needed elsewhere.\n\nNow I need to refactor the page file to work as a Server Component instead.\n\nI'll remove the `\"use client\"` directive and the client-side hook imports, make the component async to accept the `params` prop, and call `getUserProfile` directly with error handling. The display logic stays the same, and I can drop the `Skeleton` imports since there's no loading state in SSR. One thing to watch though—`UserTimeline` is marked as a Client Component, but looking at it more closely, it might not actually need that directive...\n\nLet me check if `JsonChip` requires client-side rendering.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":382,"cache_read_input_tokens":54529,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":382,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"210aa803-a4e1-4c9d-860c-765ebdce1d01","uuid":"f8ece032-e233-4170-9512-af523a8d423c"}
